<a href="javascript:card_browser(233)">Anduin Wilderland</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(238)">Shores of Nen Hithoel</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(242)">Summit of Amon Hen</a><br>
<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> As i said in my description of the deck it is just an update of my first deck. After reading the reveiws and a bit of playtesting i have changed quite a few cards and trimmed the deck up a little. I will try to go over all the points that i did in the first strategy section so no one will have to go back and reread anything<br>
<br>
Starting: <br>
You will probably want to bid two burdens and make your opponent go first. If they bid higher than that they will probably go first anyway and get Sam with the Green Drogon Inn. That is fine because the Nazgul want the early sites to really be effective. <br>
<br>
Fellowship:<br>
On the fellowship side Aragorn is your main fighter. You have the prancing pony to get him out and if they are not using it then you have three of him in your deck and three Ulaire Nelya in you deck to replace thier site one with. If Nelya is in your hand then he will always be able to come out at site two. At the Weatherhills he has no roaming and is deploy-1 and the site gives you 3. So as long as Frodo moves there then it gives you the 4 you need to bring him out. One of the first things I did when i redesigned my deck was to add more Aragorn. All the man cards in this deck are for Aragorn so once he is out they can all be played on him. Except for the versatilities which you may have to hold until you need one. The last alliance of elves and men is also for Aragorn. When he has this and his sword he is a beast. When he has his bow and Saga of Elendil he has four shots that he can give. Combined with Legolas and Tale of Gil-Galad they can combine to give 7 shots of aimed archery, but this is nothing that you dont already know because this is a very popular strategy. <br>
<br>
One that i use that is not that popular is the Galadriel and her mirror combo. I see this as one of the more powerful strategies in the game. You get to look at four cards in your opponents hand and remove two during your fellowship. This is awsome.That huge beatdown that your opponent has been saving up for. BAM. there goes two of his badest minions, or that versatility that he has been saving for a late game run. BOOM. gone. She also has other great game text. That Elrond that would normally cost 4, = free. Also the Celeborn can be free. Once Celeborn is out with Galadreil then you can use the mirror twice every fellowship phase. Or if you have Elrond out too, then you can draw two cards every fellowship phase instead of just one. This is called card advantage and these combos let you exploit that to maximum potential. But once again this is all nothing that you guys dont already know. I dont know why every deck out there isnt running this strategy. I have the Gwemegil in here but no bow of the galadrium. Arwen&#39;s sword is in here because is has a definite purose. It makes her strength plus two and pumpable. Leglas&#39;s bow just isnt that useful. Right now Legolas is a weak fighter and not meant for that purpose. Plus one power is not that important and he doesnt win enough skirmishes for it to be worth a card slot.<br>
<br>
The main reason Gandolf is in the deck is for sleep, caradhras. This card is just so broken. It gets rid of all conditions. Come on, what were you guys at decipher thinking. Well, i definitely use it in my deck. The rare Gandolf is also a must. With the Glamdring he can be power 11 in this deck. That is powerful enough to take on most minions. One problem i have encountered in playtesting is conditions. So i put Albert Dreary in there ( along with the sleeps ) for exactly that purpose. A card that works perfect with that is A wizard is never late. Lets you go get Gandolf or Dreary, whichever you dont have at the time. I would like to have put all the good Gandolf cards in here but i just didnt have room.<br>
Another card i put in was Power According To His Stature ( PATHS ). Playtesting has shown me the power of this card and if i had another one it would be in the deck too. One more card i put in is Thrarin - Dwarven Speedbump. He is a good ally to have around with all those monstorous minions that are out there right now. He can save one of your main guys like Aragorn of Gandolf by being fed to the Cave Troll or Balrog. Even though not tournament legal yet, in pick up games and playtesting, there he is. <br>
<br>
Shadow:<br>
The Nazgul side of the strategy is much more simple to explain. Four blade tips are a must and a given. This card is a garanteed extra wound is nothing else, plus they will have to burn one of there athelas or a sleep jsut to get rid of it. I have decided to only use the feirce nazgul. &#39;Cause hey two attacks are a lot better than one. nuff said. Morgul gates is a must have in any Nazgul deck. I used to play with just two but i made it a point to go out and get two more. I have seen the power of this card through playtesting. Another card that i had to have used on me before i saw its power was relentless charge. Everyone uses archery in some form or fashion. Most use Greenleaf and Aragorn&#39;s Bow. How many times have you seen one or both of them exhausted. Exert a nazgul to wound every archer companion. POWERFUL. The morgul blade is to help reuse those blade tips. I use three witch kings and two pale blades for a reason. The witch king with his sword eats people. At the weatherhills witch king can come out at site 2 with a pale blade and a morgul gates for nine. If they pull aragorn with the pony and move then that is 10. 4 for aragorn 3 ( at least ) for moving and 3 from the site. They should lose at least one character if not two to that. Most people will empty their hand on the first turn and that is where they will pay if you have a good hand. One of the main reasons  that i use Nazgul is nonone likes to double move on them. Not even early. Especially not early. Most other decks allow you to double move early and put the pressure on late, but not Nazgul. They put the pressure on early and keep it on. I also added the morgul skulkers. They help you recycle cards like the with king/pale blade and morgul gates for that late game beatdown.<br>
<br>
Miscellaneous:<br>
Ive tried to cover most of the cards in the deck. Anything left out i hope will be self-explanitory. The armor for Aragorn is when he has to fight uruk-hai or any damage + 1 minion. The sites in the deck were mostly chosen because they are anti ranger&#39;s versatility. Only ones that are, are 3 and 8. 3 because its the ford : ) and eight because they all are. 7 actually is a versatility site but with no archery they will still have to fight my Nazgul. Just play smart and this deck should be able to win any game that you play. Also when you play uruk-hai do not put out gandolf unless aragorn or another companion is already dead. Savagery to match their numbers is lethal. Once mines of moria is released throw the common balrog in here. The rare one wont work. That&#39;s if the spoiler in saw was correct. I dont know how the twilight nazgul will play out but adjust the deck accordingly. Right now putting burdens on the ringbearer with nazgul is quite difficult but if it becomes the dominant strategy then add all those cards and throw in another Enquea or two. <br>
<br>
That&#39;s all i can think of so please enjoy and i hope you were able ot pick something up that you already didnt know. Thanks for reading and reveiwing my deck.<br>
